<fr:tree toc="true" numbered="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
  <fr:frontmatter>
    <fr:anchor>1135</fr:anchor>
    <fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-ii-2.1.17</fr:addr>
    <fr:route>hodge-theory-ii-2.1.17.xml</fr:route>
    <fr:authors />
    <fr:number>2.1.17</fr:number>
  </fr:frontmatter>
  <fr:mainmatter>
    <fr:p>The reader can generalise these definitions to Hodge <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex>-structures of weight <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex> (<fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-ii-2.1.12" href="hodge-theory-ii-2.1.12.xml" number="2.1.12" />).</fr:p>
  </fr:mainmatter>
  <fr:backmatter>
    <fr:tree toc="false" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
      <fr:frontmatter>
        <fr:title text="Context">Context</fr:title>
        <fr:authors />
      </fr:frontmatter>
      <fr:mainmatter>
        <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="false" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:anchor>1136</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-ii-2.1</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>hodge-theory-ii-2.1.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Hodge Theory II › Hodge structures › Pure structures"><fr:link type="local" href="hodge-theory-ii-2.xml" addr="hodge-theory-ii-2" title="Hodge Theory II › Hodge structures"><fr:link type="local" href="hodge-theory-ii.xml" addr="hodge-theory-ii" title="Hodge Theory II">Hodge Theory II</fr:link> › Hodge structures</fr:link> › Pure structures</fr:title>
            <fr:authors />
            <fr:number>2.1</fr:number>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:anchor>813</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-ii-2.1.1</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>hodge-theory-ii-2.1.1.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:authors />
                <fr:number>2.1.1</fr:number>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <fr:p>In all the following, we denote by <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {C}]]></fr:tex> an algebraic closure of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {R}]]></fr:tex>, and we do not suppose to have chosen a root <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[i]]></fr:tex> of the equation <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x^2+1=0]]></fr:tex>.
    The theory will be invariant under complex conjugation (cf. <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-ii-2.1.14" href="hodge-theory-ii-2.1.14.xml" number="2.1.14" />).</fr:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
              <fr:backmatter />
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:anchor>814</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-ii-2.1.2</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>hodge-theory-ii-2.1.2.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:authors />
                <fr:number>2.1.2</fr:number>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <fr:p>We denote by <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> the real algebraic group <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {C}^*]]></fr:tex>, given by restriction of scalars à la Weil from <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {C}]]></fr:tex> to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {R}]]></fr:tex> of the group <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {G}_\mathrm {m}]]></fr:tex>:
    <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[       \begin {aligned}         S         &= \prod _{\mathbb {C}{/}\mathbb {R}}\mathbb {G}_\mathrm {m}       \\S(\mathbb {R})         &= \mathbb {C}^*.       \end {aligned}     ]]></fr:tex></fr:p>
                <fr:p>The group <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> is a torus, i.e. it is connected and of multiplicative type.
    It is thus described by the free abelian group of finite type
    <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[       X(S)       = \operatorname {Hom}(S_\mathbb {C},\mathbb {G}_\mathrm {m})       = \underline {\operatorname {Hom}}(S,\mathbb {G}_\mathrm {m})(\mathbb {C})     ]]></fr:tex>
    of its complex characters, endowed with the action of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Gal}(\mathbb {C}{/}\mathbb {R})=\mathbb {Z}{/}(2)]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
                <fr:p>The group <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X(S)]]></fr:tex> has generators <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[z]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\overline {z}]]></fr:tex>, which induce (respectively) the identity and complex conjugation:
    <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[       \mathbb {C}^*       = S(\mathbb {R})       \to  S(\mathbb {C})       \to  \mathbb {G}_\mathrm {m}(\mathbb {C})       = \mathbb {C}^*.     ]]></fr:tex>
    Complex conjugation exchanges <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[z]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\overline {z}]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
              <fr:backmatter />
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:anchor>815</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-ii-2.1.3</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>hodge-theory-ii-2.1.3.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:authors />
                <fr:number>2.1.3</fr:number>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <fr:p>We have a canonical map

    <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>816</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-ii-2.1.3.1</fr:addr><fr:route>hodge-theory-ii-2.1.3.1.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Equation</fr:taxon><fr:authors /><fr:number>2.1.3.1</fr:number></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[         w\colon  \mathbb {G}_\mathrm {m}\to  S       \tag{2.1.3.1}       ]]></fr:tex></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree>

    
    that, on the real points, induces the inclusion of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {R}^*]]></fr:tex> into <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {C}^*]]></fr:tex>.
    We have

    <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>817</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-ii-2.1.3.2</fr:addr><fr:route>hodge-theory-ii-2.1.3.2.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Equation</fr:taxon><fr:authors /><fr:number>2.1.3.2</fr:number></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[         zw         = \overline {z}w         = \mathrm {Id}.       \tag{2.1.3.2}       ]]></fr:tex></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree></fr:p>
                <fr:p>We also have a map

    <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>818</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-ii-2.1.3.3</fr:addr><fr:route>hodge-theory-ii-2.1.3.3.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Equation</fr:taxon><fr:authors /><fr:number>2.1.3.3</fr:number></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[         N\colon  S\to \mathbb {G}_\mathrm {m}       \tag{2.1.3.3}       ]]></fr:tex></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree>

    that on the real points can be identified with the norm <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[N_{\mathbb {C}{/}\mathbb {R}}\colon \mathbb {C}^*\to \mathbb {R}^*]]></fr:tex>.
    We have

    <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>819</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-ii-2.1.3.4</fr:addr><fr:route>hodge-theory-ii-2.1.3.4.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Equation</fr:taxon><fr:authors /><fr:number>2.1.3.4</fr:number></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[         N = z\overline {z}       \tag{2.1.3.4}       ]]></fr:tex></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree>

    <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>820</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-ii-2.1.3.5</fr:addr><fr:route>hodge-theory-ii-2.1.3.5.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Equation</fr:taxon><fr:authors /><fr:number>2.1.3.5</fr:number></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[         N\circ  w         = (x\mapsto  x^2).       \tag{2.1.3.5}       ]]></fr:tex></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree></fr:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
              <fr:backmatter />
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:anchor>821</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-ii-2.1.4</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>hodge-theory-ii-2.1.4.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
                <fr:authors />
                <fr:number>2.1.4</fr:number>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <fr:p>A <fr:em>real Hodge structure</fr:em> is a real vector space <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[V]]></fr:tex> of finite dimension endowed with an action of the real algebraic group <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
              <fr:backmatter />
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:anchor>822</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-ii-2.1.5</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>hodge-theory-ii-2.1.5.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:authors />
                <fr:number>2.1.5</fr:number>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <fr:p>By the general theory of groups of multiplicative type, giving a real Hodge structure on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[V]]></fr:tex> is equivalent to giving a bigrading <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[V^{p,q}]]></fr:tex> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[V_\mathbb {C}=\mathbb {C}\otimes _\mathbb {R} V]]></fr:tex> that satisfies <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\overline {V^{pq}}=V^{qp}]]></fr:tex>.
    The action of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> and the bigrading are mutually determined via the condition:

    <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>823</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-ii-2.1.5.1</fr:addr><fr:route>hodge-theory-ii-2.1.5.1.xml</fr:route><fr:authors /><fr:number>2.1.5.1</fr:number></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>On <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[V^{pq}]]></fr:tex>, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> acts by multiplication by <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[z^p\overline {z}^q]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree></fr:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
              <fr:backmatter />
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:anchor>824</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-ii-2.1.6</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>hodge-theory-ii-2.1.6.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:authors />
                <fr:number>2.1.6</fr:number>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <fr:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(\mathbb {C},\times )]]></fr:tex> be the multiplicative monoid, and let
    <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[       \overline {S}       = \prod _{\mathbb {C}{/}\mathbb {R}} (\mathbb {C},\times ).     ]]></fr:tex>
    If <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[V]]></fr:tex> is a real vector space, then we can show that it is equivalent to either give an action of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\overline {S}]]></fr:tex> on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[V]]></fr:tex> or to give a bigrading <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[V^{pq}]]></fr:tex> on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[V]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\overline {V^{pq}}=V^{qp}]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[V^{pq}=0]]></fr:tex> for <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p<0]]></fr:tex> or <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[q<0]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
              <fr:backmatter />
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:anchor>825</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-ii-2.1.7</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>hodge-theory-ii-2.1.7.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:authors />
                <fr:number>2.1.7</fr:number>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <fr:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[V]]></fr:tex> be a real Hodge structure, defined by a representation <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\sigma ]]></fr:tex> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> and a bigrading <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[V^{pq}]]></fr:tex>.
    The grading of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[V_\mathbb {C}]]></fr:tex> by the <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[V_\mathbb {C}^n=\sum _{p+q=n}V^{pq}]]></fr:tex> is then defined over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {R}]]></fr:tex>.
    We call this the <fr:em>weight grading</fr:em>.
    On <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[V^n=V\cap  V_\mathbb {C}^n]]></fr:tex>, the representation <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\sigma  w]]></fr:tex> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {G}_\mathrm {m}]]></fr:tex> is multiplication by <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x^n]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
                <fr:p>We say that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[V]]></fr:tex> is <fr:em>of weight <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex></fr:em> if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[V^{pq}=0]]></fr:tex> for <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p+q\neq  n]]></fr:tex>, i.e. if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\sigma  w]]></fr:tex> is multiplication by <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x^n]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
              <fr:backmatter />
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:anchor>826</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-ii-2.1.8</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>hodge-theory-ii-2.1.8.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:authors />
                <fr:number>2.1.8</fr:number>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <fr:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[V]]></fr:tex> be a real Hodge structure.
    The <fr:em>Hodge filtration</fr:em> on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[V_\mathbb {C}]]></fr:tex> is defined by
    <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[       F^p(V_\mathbb {C})       = \sum _{p'\geqslant  p} V^{p'q'}.     ]]></fr:tex></fr:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
              <fr:backmatter />
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:p>By <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-ii-1.2.6" href="hodge-theory-ii-1.2.6.xml" number="1.2.6" />, we have:</fr:p>
            <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:anchor>827</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-ii-2.1.9</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>hodge-theory-ii-2.1.9.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:taxon>Proposition</fr:taxon>
                <fr:authors />
                <fr:number>2.1.9</fr:number>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <fr:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex> be an integer.
    The construction <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-ii-2.1.8" href="hodge-theory-ii-2.1.8.xml" number="2.1.8" /> establishes an equivalence of categories between:

    
 <html:ol xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">
      
 <html:li style="list-style-type: &quot;(a) &quot;">
        the category of real Hodge structures of weight <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex>;
      </html:li>

      
 <html:li style="list-style-type: &quot;(b) &quot;">
        the category of pairs consisting of a real vector space <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[V]]></fr:tex> of finite dimension and of a filtration <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[F]]></fr:tex> on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[V_\mathbb {C}=\mathbb {C}\otimes _\mathbb {R} V]]></fr:tex> that is <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex>-opposite to its complex conjugate <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\overline {F}]]></fr:tex>.
      </html:li>

    </html:ol></fr:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
              <fr:backmatter />
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:anchor>828</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-ii-2.1.10</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>hodge-theory-ii-2.1.10.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
                <fr:authors />
                <fr:number>2.1.10</fr:number>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <fr:p>A <fr:em>Hodge structure</fr:em> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H]]></fr:tex>, of weight <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex>, consists of

    
 <html:ol xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">
      
 <html:li style="list-style-type: &quot;(a) &quot;">
        a <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {Z}]]></fr:tex>-module <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H_\mathbb {Z}]]></fr:tex> of finite type (the "<fr:em>integral lattice</fr:em>");
      </html:li>

      
 <html:li style="list-style-type: &quot;(b) &quot;">
        a real Hodge structure of weight <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex> on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H_\mathbb {R}=\mathbb {R}\otimes _\mathbb {Z} H_\mathbb {Z}]]></fr:tex>.
      </html:li>

    </html:ol></fr:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
              <fr:backmatter />
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:anchor>829</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-ii-2.1.11</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>hodge-theory-ii-2.1.11.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:authors />
                <fr:number>2.1.11</fr:number>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <fr:p>A morphism <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f\colon  H\to  H']]></fr:tex> is a homomorphism <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f\colon  H_\mathbb {Z}\to  H'_\mathbb {Z}]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f_\mathbb {R}\colon  H_\mathbb {R}\to  H'_\mathbb {R}]]></fr:tex> is compatible with the action of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> (i.e. such that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f_\mathbb {C}]]></fr:tex> is compatible with the bigrading, or with the Hodge filtration).</fr:p>
                <fr:p>Hodge structures of weight <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex> form an abelian category.
    If <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H]]></fr:tex> is of weight <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex>, and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H']]></fr:tex> is of weight <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n']]></fr:tex>, then we define a Hodge structure <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H\otimes  H']]></fr:tex> of weight <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n+n']]></fr:tex> by the equations:

    
 <html:ol xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">
      
 <html:li style="list-style-type: &quot;(a) &quot;">
        <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(H\otimes  H')_\mathbb {Z}=H_\mathbb {Z}\otimes  H'_\mathbb {Z}]]></fr:tex>;
      </html:li>

      
 <html:li style="list-style-type: &quot;(b) &quot;">
        the action of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(H\otimes  H')_\mathbb {R}=H_\mathbb {R}\otimes  H'_\mathbb {R}]]></fr:tex> is the tensor product of the actions of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H_\mathbb {R}]]></fr:tex> and on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H'_\mathbb {R}]]></fr:tex>.
      </html:li>

    </html:ol></fr:p>
                <fr:p>The bigrading (resp. Hodge filtration) of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(H\otimes  H')_\mathbb {C}=H_\mathbb {C}\otimes  H'_\mathbb {C}]]></fr:tex> is the tensor product of the bigradings (resp. Hodge filtrations (cf. <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-ii-1.1.12" href="hodge-theory-ii-1.1.12.xml" number="1.1.12" />)) of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H_\mathbb {C}]]></fr:tex> and of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H'_\mathbb {C}]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
                <fr:p>We define in an analogous manner the Hodge structure <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\underline {\operatorname {Hom}}(H,H')]]></fr:tex> (of weight <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n'-n]]></fr:tex>), the Hodge structures <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\wedge ^p H]]></fr:tex> (of weight <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[pn]]></fr:tex>), and the dual Hodge structure <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H^*]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
                <fr:p>The <fr:em>internal hom</fr:em> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\underline {\operatorname {Hom}}]]></fr:tex> above and the homomorphism group, are related by:

    <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>676</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-ii-2.1.11.1</fr:addr><fr:route>hodge-theory-ii-2.1.11.1.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Remark</fr:taxon><fr:authors /><fr:number>2.1.11.1</fr:number></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Hom}(H,H')]]></fr:tex> is the subgroup of
        <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[           \underline {\operatorname {Hom}}(H,H')_\mathbb {Z}           = \operatorname {Hom}_\mathbb {Z}(H_\mathbb {Z},H'_\mathbb {Z})         ]]></fr:tex>
        consisting of elements of degree <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(0,0)]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree></fr:p>
                <fr:p>The actions of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H_\mathbb {R}]]></fr:tex>, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H'_\mathbb {R}]]></fr:tex>, and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\underline {\operatorname {Hom}}(H,H')_\mathbb {R}=\operatorname {Hom}(H_\mathbb {R},H'_\mathbb {R})]]></fr:tex> are related by
    <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[       s(f(x))       = s(f)(s(x)).     ]]></fr:tex>
    This means that if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex> is of degree <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(0,0)]]></fr:tex>, i.e. invariant under <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex>, then it commutes with the action of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
              <fr:backmatter />
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:anchor>830</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-ii-2.1.12</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>hodge-theory-ii-2.1.12.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:authors />
                <fr:number>2.1.12</fr:number>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <fr:p>If <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> is a Noetherian subring of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {R}]]></fr:tex>, then we define a <fr:em>Hodge <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex>-structure of weight <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex></fr:em> to consist of an <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex>-module <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H_A]]></fr:tex> of finite type along with a real Hodge structure of weight <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex> on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H_\mathbb {R}=H_A\otimes _A\mathbb {R}]]></fr:tex>.
    This definition is mostly used for <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A=\mathbb {Q}]]></fr:tex>.
    A Hodge <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex>-structure consists of an <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex>-module <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H_A]]></fr:tex> of finite type along with a real Hodge structure on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H_\mathbb {R}=H_A\otimes _A\mathbb {R}]]></fr:tex> such that the weight grading is defined over the field of fractions of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
              <fr:backmatter />
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:anchor>831</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-ii-2.1.13</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>hodge-theory-ii-2.1.13.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
                <fr:authors />
                <fr:number>2.1.13</fr:number>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <fr:p>The <fr:em>Tate Hodge structure <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {Z}(1)]]></fr:tex></fr:em> is the Hodge structure of weight <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[-2]]></fr:tex>, of rank <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[1]]></fr:tex>, of pure bidegree <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(-1,-1)]]></fr:tex>, with integral lattice <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[2\pi  i\mathbb {Z}\subset \mathbb {C}]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
                <fr:p>The action of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> is thus given by multiplication with the inverse of the norm (<fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-ii-2.1.3.3" href="hodge-theory-ii-2.1.3.3.xml" taxon="Equation" number="2.1.3.3" />).</fr:p>
                <fr:p>For <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n\in \mathbb {Z}]]></fr:tex>, we define <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {Z}(n)]]></fr:tex> as the <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex>-th tensor power of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {Z}(1)]]></fr:tex>, so <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {Z}(n)]]></fr:tex> is the Hodge structure of weight <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[-2n]]></fr:tex>, of rank <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[1]]></fr:tex>, of pure bidegree <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(-n,-n)]]></fr:tex>, with integral lattice <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(2\pi  i)^n\mathbb {Z}\subset \mathbb {C}]]></fr:tex>.
    THe action of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> is multiplication by <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[N(x)^{-n}]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
              <fr:backmatter />
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:anchor>832</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-ii-2.1.14</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>hodge-theory-ii-2.1.14.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:authors />
                <fr:number>2.1.14</fr:number>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <fr:p>The choice in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {C}]]></fr:tex> of a solution <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[i]]></fr:tex> of the equation <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x^2+1=0]]></fr:tex> determines, on each complex variety <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> of pure dimension <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex>, an orientation <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {or}_i(X)]]></fr:tex>.
    Replace <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[i]]></fr:tex> by <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[-i]]></fr:tex> gives
    <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[       \operatorname {or}_{-i}(X)       = (-1)^n\operatorname {or}_i(X).     ]]></fr:tex></fr:p>
                <fr:p>The choice of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[i]]></fr:tex> also defines an element <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[C]]></fr:tex> of order 4 in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S(\mathbb {R})]]></fr:tex>, given by the image of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[i]]></fr:tex> under the isomorphism <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S(\mathbb {R})\simeq \mathbb {C}^*]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
                <fr:p>Finally, it also defines an isomorphism between <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {Z}]]></fr:tex> and the integral lattice of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {Z}(n)]]></fr:tex>, given by multiplication by <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(2\pi  i)^n]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
                <fr:p>When <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[i]]></fr:tex>, an orientation of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex>, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[C]]></fr:tex>, or an identification <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {Z}\sim \mathbb {Z}(n)_\mathbb {Z}]]></fr:tex> appear in an equation, it is implicitly understood that they all follow from a single choice of the same <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[i]]></fr:tex>, and that by replacing <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[i]]></fr:tex> with <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[-i]]></fr:tex> we obtain an equivalent equation.</fr:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
              <fr:backmatter />
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:anchor>833</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-ii-2.1.15</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>hodge-theory-ii-2.1.15.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
                <fr:authors />
                <fr:number>2.1.15</fr:number>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <fr:p>A <fr:em>polarisation</fr:em> of a Hodge structure <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H]]></fr:tex> of weight <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex> is a homomorphism
    <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[       (x,y)\colon  H\otimes  H \to  \mathbb {Z}(-n)     ]]></fr:tex>
    such that the real bilinear form <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(2\pi  i)^n(x,Cy)]]></fr:tex> on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H_\mathbb {R}]]></fr:tex> is symmetric and positive definite.</fr:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
              <fr:backmatter />
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:anchor>834</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-ii-2.1.16</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>hodge-theory-ii-2.1.16.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:authors />
                <fr:number>2.1.16</fr:number>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <fr:p>The <fr:em>real Tate Hodge structure</fr:em> is the real Hodge structure <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {R}(1)]]></fr:tex> underlying <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {Z}(1)]]></fr:tex>.
    We similarly define <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {R}(n)]]></fr:tex> as underlying <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {Z}(1)]]></fr:tex>.
    A polarisation of a <fr:em>real</fr:em> Hodge structure of weight <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex> is a homomorphism
    <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[       (x,y)\colon  H\otimes  H\to  \mathbb {R}(-n)     ]]></fr:tex>
    such that the real bilinear form <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(2\pi  i)^n(x,Cy)]]></fr:tex> on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H_\mathbb {R}]]></fr:tex> is symmetric and positive definite.
    A polarisation is entirely defined by the positive definite quadratic form <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(2\pi  i)^n(x,Cy)]]></fr:tex> on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H_\mathbb {R}]]></fr:tex>, imposed with only the condition of being invariant under the compact sub-torus of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> given by the kernel of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[N]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
                <fr:p>We have
    <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[       (x,y)       = (Cx,Cy)       = (y,C^2x)       = (-1)^n(y,x).     ]]></fr:tex>
    The form <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(x,y)]]></fr:tex> is thus symmetric or alternating, depending on the parity of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
              <fr:backmatter />
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:anchor>835</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-ii-2.1.17</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>hodge-theory-ii-2.1.17.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:authors />
                <fr:number>2.1.17</fr:number>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <fr:p>The reader can generalise these definitions to Hodge <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex>-structures of weight <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex> (<fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-ii-2.1.12" href="hodge-theory-ii-2.1.12.xml" number="2.1.12" />).</fr:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
              <fr:backmatter />
            </fr:tree>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
      </fr:mainmatter>
      <fr:backmatter />
    </fr:tree>
    <fr:tree toc="false" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
