          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:anchor>1137</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-ii-2.1.12</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>hodge-theory-ii-2.1.12.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:authors />
            <fr:number>2.1.12</fr:number>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>If <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> is a Noetherian subring of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {R}]]></fr:tex>, then we define a <fr:em>Hodge <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex>-structure of weight <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex></fr:em> to consist of an <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex>-module <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H_A]]></fr:tex> of finite type along with a real Hodge structure of weight <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex> on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H_\mathbb {R}=H_A\otimes _A\mathbb {R}]]></fr:tex>.
    This definition is mostly used for <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A=\mathbb {Q}]]></fr:tex>.
    A Hodge <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex>-structure consists of an <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex>-module <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H_A]]></fr:tex> of finite type along with a real Hodge structure on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H_\mathbb {R}=H_A\otimes _A\mathbb {R}]]></fr:tex> such that the weight grading is defined over the field of fractions of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
